               <head>Tuhfat al-muluk</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>1 copy of Tuḥfat al-mulūk</summary>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85041100" n="1" xml:id="Uk_Or_15598-item1">
                     <title xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="work_8606">Tuḥfat al-mulūk</title>
                     <title xml:lang="per" key="work_8606">تحفة الملوک</title>
                     <note>
                        <p>A didactic tract on ethics and government, also known by the title <title>Tuḥfat al-vuzarā</title>, comprising 40 briefsections (bāb), each containing four maxims. 
                        </p>
                        <p>Author unknown. </p>
                        <p>The present manuscript was copied and illuminated by or for <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="person_f7742" role="scr">Sayyid Yūsuf Majd al-Udabā</persName>, and illustrated by his son, for presentation to the heir apparent Prince (later Shah) <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="person_64009470" ref="http://lccn.loc.gov/n79039761" role="pat">Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, 1919-1980</persName>This is evident from two inscriptions in illuminated panels at the foot of f. 8v and the head and foot of f. 9r, together with the presence of his portrait on f. 9r. The latter is signed by <q>Sayyid Ḥusayn pisar-i Majd al-Udabā</q>. 
                        </p>
                        <p>Includes a drawing of Prince Mohammad Reza on f. 9r by <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="person_f7736" role="art">Sayyid Ḥusayn, son of Majd al-Udabā</persName>, dated 1304 shamsī/1925-6. 
                        </p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="per">Persian</textLang>
                     <filiation />
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
